","Fibrillin","Collagen","Laminin","Fibronectin"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElastin\u003C/strong\u003E is the dominant extracellular matrix protein in elastic arteries, particularly in the tunica media layer where it is arranged in concentric elastic lamellae. These elastic lamellae allow the arterial walls to expand during systole and recoil during diastole, helping to maintain continuous blood flow and blood pressure throughout the cardiac cycle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFibrillin\u003C/strong\u003E is a glycoprotein that forms microfibrils which provide a scaffold for elastin assembly, but it is not the dominant protein. \u003Cstrong\u003ECollagen\u003C/strong\u003E, while important for providing tensile strength, is present in lower quantities than elastin in elastic arteries. \u003Cstrong\u003ELaminin\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily found in basement membranes and is not a major component of arterial walls. \u003Cstrong\u003EFibronectin\u003C/strong\u003E is involved in cell adhesion and wound healing but is not a dominant protein in arterial extracellular matrix.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe high elastin content (up to 40% by dry weight) in elastic arteries is crucial for their function in dampening pressure fluctuations created by cardiac contractions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Elastin is the dominant extracellular matrix protein in elastic arteries, providing elasticity and resilience to the vessel walls.","Elastic arteries like the aorta contain up to 40% elastin by dry weight in their walls.","The arrangement of elastin in concentric lamellae allows arteries to expand and recoil during the cardiac cycle."],"references":["Tr\u0119bacz H, Barzycka A. Mechanical Properties and Functions of Elastin: An Overview. Biomolecules. 2023 Mar 22;13(3):574. doi: 10.3390/biom13030574. PMID: 36979509; PMCID: PMC10046833.","Tucker WD, Arora Y, Mahajan K. 